This species may be separated from other 

Charinus

in Amazonia and northern South America by means of the following combination of characters: carapace reddish-brown with darker mottling (
Fig. 29A
); six setae on anterior margin of carapace; median eyes and median ocular tubercle present (
Fig. 29C
); lateral eyes well developed; tritosternum projected anteriorly with typical setation (
Fig. 29B
); other sternal platelets wider than long; pedipalp femur with five dorsal spines and five ventral spines (
Fig. 3C–D
); pedipalp femur with additional small spine proximal and ventral to ventral spine 1; pedipalp patella with five or six dorsal spines (
Fig. 29E
); pedipalp patella with four ventral spines (
Fig. 29F
); pedipalp tarsus with two dorsal spines (
Fig. 29D
); tibia of leg I with 23 articles, tarsus I with 43 articles; leg IV basitibia with four pseudo-articles; female gonopod cushion-like and markedly sclerotized basally (
Fig. 5C–D
).

Holotype GUYANA • sex unspecified; Kamakusa ; [ 05°57′ N , 59°54′ W ];
4 Nov. 1922
; Lang and LaVarre leg.; AMNH [not examined].

